<subSubSection id="C3126501D815FF9A3CB4FC733379FF7F" pageId="64" pageNumber="1023" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BB7368AD815FF9A3CB4FC733379FF7F" blockId="64.[151,1058,969,1049]" pageId="64" pageNumber="1023">
E t y m o l o g y: The trivial name, 
<emphasis id="B97CEA98D815FF9A3E0BFC7330BBF8B8" box="[552,644,969,990]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="1023">atrafinus</emphasis>
, is a Latin compound name that stems from 
<emphasis id="B97CEA98D815FF9A3CECFC5D32C6F89A" box="[207,249,999,1020]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="1023">atra</emphasis>
(= black) and 
<emphasis id="B97CEA98D815FF9A3DB3FC5C3383F89D" box="[400,444,998,1019]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="1023">finis</emphasis>
(= end); with regard to the black coloration at the distal 1/3 of the elytal disc.
</paragraph>
